The image in your example uses 2 separate elements: the div with text and the image, positioned one on top of the other.

You need position: relative for the text div, and position:absolute for the image. Here&#39;s an example; the key elements are the `position:` of both divs and the `top:` and `right:` of the second one:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

     .text {
      position: relative;
      width: 400px;
      height: 200px;
      background-color:black;
      color:white
      }
      
     .image {
      position: absolute;
      top: 100px;
      right:25px;
      width: 200px;
      height: 150px;
      border: 2px solid red;
      background-color:grey;
     }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;body&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;text&quot;&gt;This is the div with white text on black background.
      &lt;div class=&quot;image&quot;&gt;This is your image.&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

    &lt;/body&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

